<header>
  <h1>WFH CODE</h1>
  <p>BPO Remote Discipline Guide</p>
</header>

<div class="container">

<div class="card">
<p>
Working from home in BPO sounds like freedom until you realize freedom still has KPIs and someone, somewhere, is timing your bathroom breaks in spirit.
</p>

<p>
Here’s what actually matters, beyond the usual "get a headset and a quiet room" advice everyone recycles like it’s sacred knowledge.
</p>
</div>

<h2>1. Micro-distraction stacking</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>Your real enemy is not the big distraction. It is the hundreds of tiny ones.</p>

<ul>
<li>10 seconds checking your phone</li>
<li>20 seconds switching tabs</li>
<li>5 seconds thinking about something unrelated</li>
<li>Repeating this all day</li>
</ul>

<p>
Individually harmless. Collectively fatal.
</p>

<p>
WFH success is largely determined by how few mental context switches you make per hour.
</p>
</div>

<h2>2. Invisible accountability</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>
Motivation apps and productivity tricks are often overrated.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Keep work visible on your screen</li>
<li>Remove unnecessary tabs</li>
<li>Start working immediately after login</li>
</ul>

<p>
The goal is reducing decisions, not strengthening willpower.
</p>
</div>

<h2>3. Your chair affects performance</h2>

<div class="card">
<ul>
<li>Subtle fatigue</li>
<li>Slower reactions</li>
<li>More judgment errors</li>
<li>More procrastinated fixes</li>
</ul>

<p>
WFH performance often starts declining in the body before it becomes visible in work quality.
</p>
</div>

<h2>4. Transition friction</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>
Every interruption creates a restart cost.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Lunch breaks</li>
<li>Phone checks</li>
<li>Short walks away from work</li>
</ul>

<p>
The skill is not working fast. The skill is returning to focus quickly.
</p>
</div>

<h2>5. Your headset is a performance tool</h2>

<div class="card">
<ul>
<li>Audio clarity affects confidence</li>
<li>Delay creates conversational stress</li>
<li>Poor microphones increase repetition</li>
</ul>

<p>
In voice accounts, bad audio equipment can quietly create performance problems.
</p>
</div>

<h2>6. Queue fear control</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>
Many non-voice workers slow down because they fear mistakes, not because tasks are difficult.
</p>

<p>
Over-checking often damages productivity more than occasional errors.
</p>
</div>

<h2>7. Auto-skipping in back office work</h2>

<div class="card">
<ul>
<li>Skipping verification steps</li>
<li>Assuming correctness</li>
<li>Rushing confirmations</li>
</ul>

<p>
Repetition creates confidence. Too much confidence creates mistakes.
</p>
</div>

<h2>8. The invisible fatigue curve</h2>

<div class="card">
<ul>
<li>Slightly slower</li>
<li>Slightly less careful</li>
<li>Slightly more forgetful</li>
</ul>

<p>
Small declines compound into major accuracy problems.
</p>
</div>

<h2>9. Breaks are reset protocols</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>
Treat breaks as system resets, not distraction sessions.
</p>

<p>
The quality of your return matters more than the length of your break.
</p>
</div>

<h2>10. Context switching without emotional residue</h2>

<div class="card">
<p>
This is the advanced skill.
</p>

<ul>
<li>Handle the issue</li>
<li>Document it</li>
<li>Move on immediately</li>
<li>Carry no emotional baggage forward</li>
</ul>

<p>
Most burnout starts when frustration is allowed to travel from task to task.
</p>
</div>

<hr>

<div class="card">

<h2>Final Truth</h2>

<p>
WFH success in BPO is not about comfort.
</p>

<p>
It is about controlling:
</p>

<ul>
<li>Distraction leakage</li>
<li>Mental resets</li>
<li>Repetition fatigue</li>
<li>Emotional carryover</li>
</ul>

<p>
People think working from home gives freedom.
</p>

<p>
It actually gives exposure.
</p>

<p>
You see exactly how disciplined your attention really is.
</p>

